          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Wall Street bonuses set to jump:</strong> Wall Street’s biggest banks plan <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-10-01-2025-m1-6-double-digit-bonus" target="_blank">double-digit bonus</a> increases for traders and dealmakers. JPMorgan’s investment bankers could see bonuses rise by 15%, while Goldman Sachs is rumored to go even higher for some desks. The increases come after two years of subdued payouts and highlight a competitive job market. Rising interest rates slowed deals last year, but firms now reward top talent as trading and deal activity pick up.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Arm explores the acquisition of Ampere Computing:</strong> SoftBank-owned Arm Holdings is reportedly in talks to <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-10-01-2025-m2-7-acquire-ampere-computing" target="_blank">acquire Ampere Computing</a>. The company is a semiconductor designer backed by Oracle. In 2021, Ampere was valued at $8bn in a proposed minority investment by Japan’s SoftBank. Ampere’s chips are used in data centers, aligning with Arm’s push into AI and cloud markets. The deal could boost Arm’s capabilities in the competitive chip sector where rivals like Intel and Nvidia dominate.</p>
