          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Hershey’s cocoa purchase fuels market rally:</strong> Cocoa futures surged over 10% as Hershey Co. <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-10-01-2025-m3-8-seeks-approval" target="_blank">seeks approval</a> to purchase 90,000 metric tons from ICE Futures US. Analysts speculate that Hershey is securing physical stock amid volatile cocoa prices, which soared 178% last year. The cocoa market’s wild swings reflect low liquidity and high costs, making it a hot topic for commodity traders. Prices can spike more if supply remains tight in 2025.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Trump tariff fears hit copper and silver:</strong> Copper and silver prices spiked as traders braced for Trump’s potential import tariffs. <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-10-01-2025-m4-9-silver-futures-surged" target="_blank">Silver futures surged</a> to a $0.80 premium over London spot prices, and copper saw a $623-a-ton premium over London prices. Traders feared a tariff-driven supply squeeze, especially in silver, where low stockpiles could drive prices further up. TD Securities warned of a “silver squeeze” due to limited availability in Comex warehouses.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Gold steady as traders eye US data:</strong> Gold <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-10-01-2025-m5-10-held-steady-gains" target="_blank">held steady gains</a> near $2,670 as traders awaited US jobs data. The report could shape the Fed’s rate cut decisions. Lower rates generally boost gold, which gained 27% last year. Goldman Sachs delayed its $3,000 gold target to 2026, citing fewer expected rate cuts. While gold steadies, upcoming payroll data may signal the next move in bullion prices.</p>
