          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is Gresham's law?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-10-3.jpg" alt="What is Gresham's law?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Gresham's law is an economic principle stating that "bad money drives out good money." It occurs when two forms of currency with the same nominal value but different intrinsic values circulate in an economy. People tend to spend the currency with lower intrinsic value and hoard the currency with higher intrinsic value.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The concept originated during periods when gold and silver coins were used as money. When a government debased coins by reducing their precious metal content, people would hoard the higher-purity coins and use the debased ones for transactions. This behavior removed "good money" from circulation, leaving only "bad money" in use. The application of Gresham's law can be seen in the modern economy with legal tender laws. The traditional version of Gresham's law applies when all currency values are legally mandated to be recognized at face value. During the absence of effective legal tender laws, Gresham's law operates in reverse, where good money drives out bad money as people will decline to accept undervalued currency.</p>
        </mj-text>
